column163: services will continue to be provided to populations facing health disparities and to those who are at elevated risk for suicide. This includes African Americans, Asian Americans, and Hispanic/Latino/a, and LGBTQ-identified youth, who were identified by the CDC Youth Risk Behavior Survey data to be at risk in New York. Services will be provided to these youth not only in clinical settings but in out-of-school-time programs, an LGBTQ community center, foster care, and juvenile justice. According to the local community, there is also a significant refugee population and a population for whom English is not the first language or the language spoken in the home, putting this population at increased risk. Finally, there is also a large White population within the county, which is the group with the highest rates of suicide; Our quality improvement plan will also ensure that project sites adhere to the enhanced National Standards for Culturally and Linguistically Appropriate Services (CLAS) Standards in Health and Health Care (p6)

column36:
The TYSP-Mi3 team worked to provide alternative virtual training options—LivingWorks Start and AMSR—which trained a total of 116 people across both trainings. p3

To accommodate this delay in providing clinical and gatekeeper training to the 
ED workforce, we worked with both ED sites to offer LivingWorks Start, a 90-minute, self-paced suicide prevention training module that can be completed virtually. p5

During PY2, 60 Goal 3 participants completed the LivingWorks Start training across 14 organizations. In May of 2021, we were able to host two virtual AMSR trainings for the Macomb County Suicide Prevention Coalition and University of Michigan Department of Psychiatry with a total of 56 participants trained.

column89: The Suicide Risk Assessment Training was provided to 41 master's level and licensed mental health clinicians from community health providers and universities across Mississippi (p. 2).  Though some trainees worked in university settings, their primary role was to serve as mental health clinicians.
column98: Trainees included non-mental health clinicians working with children including education, childcare, community care, etc (p. 1).
column130: Training on screening tools was provided to Region 8 children's services/program staff but not to mental health professionals (p. 2, Obj 1.3).

column165: NOTE ON CATCHEMENT AREA: The MBCI has 8 federally recognized Choctaw tribal communities-Pearl River, Tucker, Bogue Chitto, Crystal Ridge, Conehatta, Bogue Homa, Standing Pine, and Red Water-situated across rural and remote areas among several counties in east central MS. Pearl River, the largest community, is the MBCI headquarters and site of the Choctaw Health Center. Another pocket of tribal members with even more limited service access resides 5 hours away in rural Henning, TN. This area includes Attala. Winston, Noxubee, Leake, Neshoba, Kemper, Scott, Newton, Smith, Jasper, and Jones Counties in MS (and Lauderdale County, TN but not sure we want to attribute the GLS program impact there).
